# JavaScript QuickSort Implementation

Here's a clean implementation of the QuickSort algorithm in JavaScript:

```javascript
function quickSort(arr, left = 0, right = arr.length - 1) {
  if (left < right) {
    const pivotIndex = partition(arr, left, right);
    quickSort(arr, left, pivotIndex - 1);  // Sort left subarray
    quickSort(arr, pivotIndex + 1, right); // Sort right subarray
  }
  return arr;
}

function partition(arr, left, right) {
  const pivotValue = arr[right];  // Choosing last element as pivot
  let partitionIndex = left;

  for (let i = left; i < right; i++) {
    if (arr[i] < pivotValue) {
      swap(arr, i, partitionIndex);
      partitionIndex++;
    }
  }

  swap(arr, right, partitionIndex); // Move pivot to its final place
  return partitionIndex;
}

function swap(arr, i, j) {
  [arr[i], arr[j]] = [arr[j], arr[i]];
}

// Example usage:
const unsortedArray = [9, 7, 5, 11, 12, 2, 14, 3, 10, 6];
console.log("Unsorted array:", unsortedArray);
const sortedArray = quickSort(unsortedArray);
console.log("Sorted array:", sortedArray);
```

## How It Works:

1. **quickSort**: The main function that implements the divide-and-conquer strategy
   - Base case: if the subarray has 0 or 1 elements, it's already sorted
   - Otherwise: partition the array and recursively sort the subarrays

2. **partition**: Rearranges elements so that:
   - All elements less than the pivot come before it
   - All elements greater than the pivot come after it
   - Returns the final index of the pivot element

3. **swap**: A helper function to swap two elements in an array

## Time Complexity:
- Average case: O(n log n)
- Worst case (rare with good pivot selection): O(n²)

